---
import SidebarCard from '../components/SidebarCard.astro';
import ClassicShell from '../layouts/ClassicShell.astro';
import { SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL, SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_KEYWORDS, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<ClassicShell
	title={`${SITE_TITLE} | About`}
	description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}
	pageTitle="About Industrial Wireless I/O"
	pageIntro="Industrial Wireless I/O is being built as an English-language field connectivity reference brand for engineers, operators, and technical teams working on remote telemetry and distributed assets."
	introLabel="About"
	keywords={[...SITE_KEYWORDS, 'about Industrial Wireless I/O']}
	breadcrumbs={[
		{ name: 'Home', path: '/' },
		{ name: 'About', path: '/about/' },
	]}
>
	<Fragment slot="left-rail">
		<SidebarCard title="Audience" eyebrow="Who It Helps">
			<ul>
				<li>Engineers comparing wireless and telemetry architectures</li>
				<li>Operators managing remote assets and uptime concerns</li>
				<li>Readers who need field-reality guidance, not just hardware lists</li>
			</ul>
		</SidebarCard>

		<SidebarCard title="Editorial Bias" eyebrow="What We Favor">
			<p>
				We favor field-tested logic, cleaner explanations, and content that respects power, enclosure,
				site access, reliability, and maintenance constraints.
			</p>
		</SidebarCard>
	</Fragment>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Editorial Thesis</p>
				<h2>Connectivity content should be grounded in field reality</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			This site is meant to become a dependable field manual for wireless I/O and telemetry decisions.
			That means architecture comparisons, reliability planning, and practical deployment guidance are
			more important than light product commentary or broad industrial trend posts.
		</p>
	</section>

	<div class="detail-grid">
		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">SEO Logic</p>
			<h3>Long-life architecture questions</h3>
			<p>
				Search demand is strongest where teams are deciding between network paths, remote asset
				strategies, and survivability tradeoffs that remain relevant for years.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Commercial Logic</p>
			<h3>Higher-value technical intent</h3>
			<p>
				Readers working through network design and field reliability problems are often closer to
				hardware, platform, and engineering-services spend than general industrial audiences.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Brand Goal</p>
			<h3>Modern field manual energy</h3>
			<p>
				The visual direction is more refined than a typical industrial blog, but the content hierarchy
				stays practical so the brand still feels precise and trustworthy.
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Planning Surface</p>
				<h2>The long-term framework is visible inside the site</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			The <a href="/topics/">topic map</a> defines the field and telemetry clusters worth building, while the
			<a href="/methodology/"> methodology page</a> explains how architecture and reliability pages should
			stay useful over time.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Reach Out</p>
				<h2>Corrections, suggestions, and future partner fit</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			For editorial notes or future business conversations, email <a href={`mailto:${SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>.
			The current stage is about building a stronger field-reference foundation first so later sponsor inventory has real credibility behind it.
		</p>
	</section>
</ClassicShell>
